    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 0,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Shoot particles at a hard sphere of radius a. Classically, only the ones aimed at the disk hit it \u2014 total target area is pi a-squared. Quantum mechanics: the area is 4 pi a-squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.21,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B01.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B01.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "t_start": 9,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Even at high energy, when many partial waves contribute, the cross-section never drops to the classical value. It stays at twice the geometric area.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.8,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "t_start": 18,
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Why does a quantum sphere collect more particles than its geometric shadow? And why does the extra piece never go away?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "card",
        "motion": "hold",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "Why does a quantum sphere collect more particles than its geometric\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B03.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "card": {
        "eyebrow": "QUANTUM MECHANICS",
        "headline": "Low energy: 4\u03c0a\u00b2. High energy: 2\u03c0a\u00b2. Why always more than \u03c0a\u00b2?",
        "dek": "The optical theorem: casting a shadow requires scattering"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 6.45,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 27,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "The classical picture misses what happens to the wave. A quantum particle is a wave that diffracts around the sphere and spreads into all solid angles \u2014 even where classically nothing should go.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.65,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "t_start": 37,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "At low energy only the s-wave matters. It scatters isotropically in all 4 pi steradians, producing 4 pi a-squared \u2014 four times the disk. Not an error: the wave has no preferred direction.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.8,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 47,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "At high energy the sphere blocks the forward beam. But blocking requires destructive interference \u2014 the forward-scattered wave must cancel the incident wave to create a dark shadow downstream.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.23,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B06.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B06.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "t_start": 59,
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "That forward-scattered wave carries probability. It contributes pi a-squared to the total cross-section on top of the pi a-squared from sideways scattering. The shadow counts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.03,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B07.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B07.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 70,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "This is the optical theorem: total cross-section equals 4 pi over k times the imaginary part of the forward scattering amplitude. It holds for any potential \u2014 even inelastic \u2014 because of unitarity.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.37,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B08.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B08.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "THE IMPLICATION",
      "t_start": 80,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Every absorbing or scattering object casts a shadow, and casting that shadow requires forward scattering that is always counted. Quantum objects can never look smaller than their geometric shadow.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.7,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B09.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B09.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "THE EXAMPLE",
      "t_start": 90,
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Illustrative: hard sphere, radius a equals 2 angstroms. Low energy, k a equals 0.1: sigma equals 4 pi a-squared, 16 times ten to the minus 20 square meters. High energy, k a equals 10: sigma approaches 2 pi a-squared.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "manim",
        "motion": "drawon"
      },
      "audio_file": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 18.05,
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-optical-theorem/clips/B10.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-optical-theorem/mp3/beat-B10.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "t_start": 102,
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Low energy: isotropic diffraction gives 4 pi a-squared. High energy: shadow formation forces 2 pi a-squared. Classical pi a-squared is always wrong. The shadow is half the price of blocking.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "card",
